, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1178–":"circa 1178–Overleden","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1230–1283":"1230–1283","1178–Female":"1178–Overleden","Abt 1178":"circa 1178","1178":"1178","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1283":"1283","about 1230":"circa 1230","England":"England","Of Conyers, England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kelfield, North Yorkshire, England":"Kelfield, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1178–":"about 1178–Deceased","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1230–1283":"1230–1283","1178–Female":"1178–Deceased","Abt 1178":"about 1178","1178":"1178","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1283":"1283","about 1230":"about 1230","England":"England","Of Conyers, England":"England, United Kingdom","Kelfield, North Yorkshire, England":"Kelfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Topping","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire):","nickname from Middle English <i>topping(e)</i> ‘hair on the head’, probably given to someone with a distinctive head of hair or forelock. See also   Topp   and   Topham  .","perhaps from an unrecorded Old English personal name <i>Topping</i>, a pet form of <i>Topp</i>. See also   Topp  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tappin","meanings":["English:","variant of   Topping  .","from the Middle English personal name <i>Tapping</i>, from Old English <i>Tæpping</i>, a pet form of the <i>Tæppa</i> seen in placenames like <i>Taplow</i>. See also   Tapp  ."]},{"name":"Toppin","meanings":["English (Cumbria): variant of   Topping  ."]},{"name":"Topham","meanings":["English (mainly northern, especially Yorkshire):","nickname from Middle English <i>Toppan</i>, of uncertain meaning. The second element is perhaps Middle English <i>pan(ne)</i> ‘(crown of the) head’, while <i>Top-</i> could be derived from several different words. If from Middle English <i>toppen</i> ‘to shave (the head)’, then <i>Toppan</i> might have been a name for a barber who provided tonsures for the clergy. Alternatively, <i>Top-</i> might represent Middle English <i>tup</i>, <i>top(pe)</i> ‘ram, male sheep’, hence ‘ram-head’, or Middle English <i>top(pe)</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>tupe</i> ‘hair on the head, tuft of hair, forelock’, denoting someone with a distinctive head of hair.","variant of   Topping  ."]},{"name":"Topp","meanings":["English: nickname, perhaps from Middle English <i>top(pe)</i>, <i>tope</i>, Old English <i>topp(a)</i> ‘hair on the head; tuft of hair’, for someone with distinctive hair. Compare   Topping  . Alternatively, from Middle English <i>top(pe)</i>, <i>tope</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>toup</i>, side-forms of Middle English <i>tup(pe)</i> ‘ram, male sheep’. A third possibility is a relationship name from the Middle English personal name <i>Top(pe)</i>, <i>Tope</i>, perhaps representing an unrecorded Old English <i>Top(p)</i> or <i>Toppa</i>, of uncertain origin, or else (especially in east and northern England) Old Norse <i>Tōpi</i>, <i>Tupe</i>; see   Toop  .","German: from Low German <i>topp</i> ‘point, tree top’, hence a topographic name from the location of the dwelling; alternatively, a metonymic occupational name or nickname from the same word in the sense ‘braid’.","German: variant of   Dopp  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Henry Topping was born about 1178, in England, United Kingdom. She married Henry Topping in Kelfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1178–":"umbes 1178–Surnud","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1230–1283":"1230–1283","1178–Female":"1178–Surnud","Abt 1178":"umbes 1178","1178":"1178","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1283":"1283","about 1230":"umbes 1230","England":"England","Of Conyers, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kelfield, North Yorkshire, England":"Kelfield, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1178–":"noin 1178–Kuollut","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1230–1283":"1230–1283","1178–Female":"1178–Kuollut","Abt 1178":"noin 1178","1178":"1178","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1283":"1283","about 1230":"noin 1230","England":"England","Of Conyers, England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kelfield, North Yorkshire, England":"Kelfield, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1178–":"environ 1178–Décédée","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1230–1283":"1230–1283","1178–Female":"1178–Décédée","Abt 1178":"environ 1178","1178":"1178","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1283":"1283","about 1230":"environ 1230","England":"Angleterre","Of Conyers, England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Kelfield, North Yorkshire, England":"Kelfield, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs Henry Topping est née environ 1178, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé Henry Topping à Kelfield, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"Abt 1178–":"um 1178–Verstorben","1200–1230":"1200–1230","1230–1283":"1230–1283","1178–Female":"1178–Verstorben","Abt 1178":"um 1178","1178":"1178","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1283":"1283","about 1230":"um 1230","England":"England","Of Conyers, England":"England, United Kingdom","Kelfield, North Yorkshire, England":"Kelfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Mrs Henry Topping wurde um 1178 in England, United Kingdom geboren. Sie hat in Kelfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom Henry Topping geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Tochter."},